    "Bryson, Diamantis, and Grant[51] who argue in a similar vein, but about the dangers of granting AI legal personhood, that natural persons could use artificial persons to shield themselves from the consequences of their conduct and Rubel, Castro, and Pham[52] who argue that enlisting technological systems into agents' decision-making processes can obscure moral responsibility for the results."
